defaultPublic AwarenessdefaultCondition 6 of the DCLG Conditions of Authorisation (CoA) requires scheme operators to adverti
defaultse the scheme, explain its purpose and potential to members, and its use to customers.  It is apparent however that work is being carried out and not notified to a local authority or scheme operator, either in ignorance or deliberately.  Instances of work 
defaultnot notified, are only likely to come to light during the CON 29 search questionnaire for the conveyance process when a property is sold or let.  
default&#xa0;
defaultConsumers often rely on advice given by a contractor on whether or not the work needs to be notified under t
defaulthe building regulations.  It is not possible to monitor the quality of this advice. Nor is it possible to monitor the number of installations where a contractor fails to notify relevant work.  Condition 19 of DCLG CoA requires scheme operators to ensure th
defaultat scheme members notify all completed work to the scheme and forw
defaultard a certificate of Building R
defaultegulations compliance to customers.  It is difficult to see how this can be effectively monitored as only the contractor is aware of installation work undertak
defaulten. 
